^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play. The hand should be made. All Vered has to do is draw trumps and play clubs. Don't pitch any clubs on the spades, pitch diamonds. She then takes 6 spades and 5 clubs and makes 11 tricks. However, if she chooses to knock out the Ace of diamonds first then she should not draw trumps, as she needs to retain control of the heart suit. As we saw, by drawing trumps first and then knocking out the DA, she lost a heart trick she should not lose. On this hand there was no reason to knock out the DA. However, on other hands there might be.|
PG| ***** 84 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, if knocking out the DA was needed, she needs to do that before drawing trumps. There are two main reasons to defer drawing trumps. The most common reason, as most of you know, is so you can ruff in dummy. The other reason, as illustrated in this hand, is so you retain control in a side suit while you knock out the defense high cards. On this hand, you cannot lose the lead when dummy is out of trumps, because you then lose heart tricks.|
