As a warm up, let us review a few important points in control bids before joining Howard. The material is from Bergen's book. |
PG| ***** 175 ***** |


FP|2|AT|^c@2^Y@3

In a game forcing auction, after a major is agreed, a bid in another suit shows a control in that suit. It is either Ace or King. Could be void or singleton. |
PG| ***** 176 ***** |


AT|

Aces and voids are first round controls. Kings and singletons are second round control.|
PG| ***** 177 ***** |


AT|

Control bids are bid up the line.|
PG| ***** 178 ***** |


AT|

If a player bypasses a suit, he denies a control in that suit.|
PG| ***** 179 ***** |


AT|

A control bid promises a control in that suit whether first-round OR second-round.|
PG| ***** 180 ***** |


AT|

A control bid at 5 level shows first-round control.|
PG| ***** 181 ***** |


AT|

A control bid in partner's long suit (usually partner opened that major) promises the Ace or King.|
PG| ***** 182 ***** |


AT|

After a Jacoby 2NT, a new suit by opener shows shortness at 3 level or a great suit at the 4 level. |
